              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3w08x281/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>for <placeName>Switzerland</placeName>.</p>\n                              <p>I presume from this circumstance<lb/> that the books arrived safely\n                                        at their<lb/> destination—&amp; that you have long<lb/>\n                                        since obtained your <hi rend=\"underline\">own</hi>\n                                        rightful<lb/> copy. I hope also that my long letter<lb/>\n                                        reached you from the “<add>?</add>” where<lb/> we then\n                                        resided. I wrote your address<lb/> quite from guess, for I\n                                        left my Occidents<lb/> with all my principal books to\n                                        be<lb/> taken charge of.</p>\n                              <p>My dear friend <persName>Miss Brettell<add>?</add></persName> has\n                                        taken<lb/> with me these charming rooms facing<lb/> the\n                                        Castle &amp; <placeName>Neckar</placeName> where we\n                                        have<lb/> not only a most romantic picture<lb/> ever before\n                                        our eyes, but also every comfort<lb/> &amp; convenience in\n                                        this beautiful House.<lb/> My <hi rend=\"underline\">good</hi>\n                                        Papa at length yielded to my<lb/> longing wish for a more\n                                                  <hi rend=\"underline\">country</hi> life &amp;<lb/>\n                                        now permits me to follow my inclination<del>s</del><lb/>\n                                        which was never in favor of a residence<lb/> in our gay\n                                        &amp; busy city of <placeName>London</placeName>!</p>\n                              <p>It is, as you may imagine, an infinite<lb/> blessing to me thus to\n                                        enjoy, in more<lb/> retirement, the glorious beauties of\n                                        nature,<lb/> &amp; my own favorite studies of Literature\n                                        &amp;<lb/> music. I do not know yet how long we<lb/> may\n                                        remain in <placeName>Heidelberg</placeName>. I think we<lb/>\n                                        shall spend <date>June</date> &amp; <date>July</date> in\n                                                  <placeName>Switzerland</placeName><lb/> (my 3d\n                                        visit) &amp; then most likely go to<lb/>\n                                        <placeName>England</placeName> for a few months as we\n                                        shall<lb/> both be <sic>anscious</sic> to see our friends\n                                        there.</p>\n                              <p>We have had a <hi rend=\"underline\">very</hi> severe winter,\n                                        but<lb/> to <hi rend=\"underline\">me</hi> the charm has been\n                                        so great<lb/> that I could not regret it. To see the<lb/>\n                                        scenery here all enveloped in its <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  >snowy</hi><lb/> mantle—has been a continual\n                                        source<lb/> of enjoyment to me &amp; the tinkling<lb/> bells\n                                        of the horses as they bore the gay<lb/> sledges along, did\n                                        not a little enhance the<lb/> beauty of the picture!</p>\n                              <p>I suppose you hear as much of<lb/> the War as we do. Some\n                                        people<lb/> are of opinion that it is the first</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3w08x281/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
