          "annotations": [
            {
              "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3w08x281/canvas/p3/annopage",
              "type": "AnnotationPage",
              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3w08x281/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>step towards the restoration of our<lb/> Nation—according to the\n                                        Prophecies.<lb/> What is your opinion? And how<lb/> goes on\n                                        your interesting work, the Bible?</p>\n                              <p>Have you heard of a <hi rend=\"underline\">small</hi> book<lb/>\n                                        published in <date>1853</date> at Chapman's in the<lb/>\n                                        <placeName>Strand, London</placeName> (price 36 s. d.) “<hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">A few words to</hi><lb/>\n                                        <hi rend=\"underline\">the Jews</hi>”? It is splendidly\n                                        written,<lb/> &amp; most touchingly beautiful—<lb/> We, as\n                                        Israelites, cannot be too grateful<lb/> to God for raising\n                                        amongst us such<lb/> an Author—so deeply imbued with the\n                                        true<lb/> spirit of Judaism. I hope it will soon<lb/> be\n                                        well known both in <placeName>England</placeName> &amp;\n                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>.<lb/> We do not\n                                        know the name of the Author<lb/> not his place of abode—he\n                                        merely adds<lb/> in the title page “by one of\n                                        themselves.”<lb/> Surely he will one day be known!<lb/> at\n                                        present all is in mystery respecting the<lb/> books. My\n                                        paper tells me to say farewell<lb/> for the present, &amp;\n                                        trusting you are in<lb/> good health, I remain dear\n                                        friend</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Your's sincerely, <persName role=\"author\">Rosa\n                                                  <add>?</add> Salsman</persName></p>\n                              <div>\n                                        <p>\n                                                  <ref target=\"Occident_PDFs/Occ_11_10.pdf\">The\n                                                  above text refers to Occident Volume 11 No. 10\n                                                  pages 515 through 520. Click here to view.</ref>\n                                        </p>\n                              </div>\n                    </body>\n          </text>\n</TEI>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3w08x281/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
